other": "strong UV or lightning-driven atmospheric processing, volcanic gas input, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Energetic atmospheric/surface processing of reduced carbon-nitrogen feedstocks yields cyanide, which accumulates in shallow pools and geothermal settings.", "reasoning": "HCN is a canonical product of reducing atmospheric discharge/UV chemistry and a central feedstock in prebiotic cyanosulfidic networks; the report identifies atmospheric UV and spark discharge as major sources and volcanic settings as compatible niches (Miller, 1953; Parker et al., 2011; Cleaves, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formamide generation from HCN hydrolysis", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted thermal/photochemical conversion", "aqueous": "true", "other": "surface pool or geothermal film, UV exposure"}, "mechanism": "Partial hydration of cyanide-derived carbon-nitrogen species furnishes formamide, a persistent C1 solvent/reactant reservoir.", "reasoning": "Formamide is widely treated as a prebiotic derivative and medium produced from HCN-related chemistry; the report specifically identifies formamide as decomposing to HCN, NH3, and H2O and as a relevant medium for serine nitrile protection chemistry (Green et al., 2023; Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Formaldehyde-ammonia adduct formation to aminomethanol", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentration with UV-exposed mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "surface pools, intermittent drying"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of ammonia to formaldehyde generates aminomethanol as the immediate precursor to methanimine/formaldimine.", "reasoning": "The RTIP-based network identifies aminomethanol as forming from formaldehyde and ammonia prior to dehydration to formaldimine; mineral concentration is introduced here only to localize reactants at the surface without changing the literature route (Li et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formic-acid-catalyzed dehydration of aminomethanol to formaldimine", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "formic acid catalysis on mineral-concentrating surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "high-energy flux from UV/lightning favored; dehydration enhanced during drying"}, "mechanism": "Aminomethanol undergoes acid-catalyzed dehydration to methanimine/formaldimine, a reactive imine hub for amino acid network formation.", "reasoning": "The literature report explicitly states that formaldimine is synthesized through HCOOH-catalyzed dehydration of aminomethanol and is a central reactive hub in the computational network for amino acid formation (Li et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydration-hydrogenation equilibration to methanimine/formaldimine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "photochemical mineral surfaces; formic acid or ammonia may mediate local proton transfer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "energetic UV/lightning-compatible setting"}, "mechanism": "Formamide-related C1 nitrogen chemistry feeds methanimine/formaldimine pools through reduction/dehydration equilibria under energetic surface conditions.", "reasoning": "The computational study identifies methanimine/formaldimine-centered networks arising from simple C1 species under energetic conditions, with formic acid and ammonia assisting hydrogen transfer and hydration-amination cycles; this reaction summarizes that literature-supported connectivity (Li et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cyanosulfidic formation of glycolonitrile from formaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-driven cyanosulfidic mineral setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich shallow pool with H2S/Cu photoredox chemistry represented by sulfide-rich mineral context, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Cyanohydrin formation captures formaldehyde as glycolonitrile, initiating homologation toward sugars and amino acid nitriles.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile is a documented early intermediate in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network connecting HCN chemistry to sugars, nucleotides, and amino acid nitriles (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson and Sutherland, 2012; Ritson and Sutherland, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Photoreductive homologation of glycolonitrile to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox, cyanosulfidic setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow surface pool; hydrated electrons generated in cyanide photoredox system"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven reductive homologation and hydrolysis convert C2 nitrile intermediates into the C2 sugar glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland established photoredox homologation logic whereby HCN-derived nitrile species are reduced and hydrolyzed to aldehydes such as glycolaldehyde in prebiotic cyanosulfidic systems (Ritson and Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Further cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-driven homologation with borate stabilization of sugars", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanide-rich shallow pools; borate buffers sugar decomposition"}, "mechanism": "Kiliani-Fischer-type homologation extends glycolaldehyde to the C3 sugar glyceraldehyde, stabilized by borate complexation.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as sequential products of HCN reductive homologation; borate minerals are consistent with stabilization of prebiotic sugars in surface settings (Ritson and Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker-type conversion of glyceraldehyde to serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface mineral concentration in UV-accessible pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN flux, NH3 available or fixed from HCN derivatives, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes Strecker-type aminonitrile formation with cyanide and ammonia to yield serine nitrile.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly identifies glyceraldehyde as the direct precursor to serine nitrile in the cyanosulfidic network and notes efficient conversion in HCN/UV-rich surface settings (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson and Sutherland, 2023; Barge and Price, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Thiophosphate-enhanced formation of serine nitrile from glycolonitrile and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thiophosphate-mediated UV chemistry on evaporitic mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "approximately 1 hour UV irradiation; reported serine nitrile yield about 16%"}, "mechanism": "Thiophosphate acts as reductant/phosphorus source and promotes rapid UV-driven homologation of glycolonitrile/HCN mixtures to serine nitrile.", "reasoning": "The deep research report specifically states that under thiophosphate-mediated UV irradiation, a mixture of glycolonitrile and HCN yields serine nitrile in about 16% yield after one hour, resolving sulfur-phosphorus compatibility issues (Ritson and Sutherland, 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Mild hydrolysis of serine nitrile to serine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous pools or rehydration phases; low temperature favored to avoid serine destruction"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis converts serine nitrile to the corresponding amino acid under mild aqueous conditions.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the classic completion step of Strecker-type pathways; low-temperature surface or pool conditions are favored because serine is thermally labile and deaminates/degrades at elevated temperature (Bada and Miller, 1968; Patel et al., 2015; Barge and Price, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Formamide-mediated N-formylation of serine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "formamide medium concentrated on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "drying films or low-water formamide-rich settings"}, "mechanism": "Serine nitrile is N-formylated in formamide-rich media, generating a protected nitrile derivative less prone to back-reaction and cyclization.", "reasoning": "Green et al. showed that amino acid nitriles such as serine nitrile can be N-formylated in formamide, furnishing protected building blocks that suppress deleterious side reactions and preserve peptide-growth potential (Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Deprotection/hydrolysis of N-formyl serine nitrile to serine", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "rehydration or neutral aqueous pool conditions"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic deprotection and nitrile hydrolysis release serine from the formyl-protected aminonitrile reservoir.", "reasoning": "This connected completion step follows directly from the role of N-formyl amino acid nitriles as protected peptide precursors in formamide chemistry; hydrolytic release in later aqueous stages is a necessary and plausible downstream transformation, though less directly quantified for serine specifically than the N-formylation step itself (Green et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Abiotic glycine hydroxymethylation to serine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild neutral aqueous conditions; tetrahydrofolate analogs or related one-carbon carriers conceptually assist"}, "mechanism": "Transfer of a hydroxymethyl equivalent from formaldehyde to glycine yields serine under mild abiotic protometabolic conditions.", "reasoning": "The report notes that glycine-serine interconversion, analogous to SHMT chemistry, can proceed abiotically in the presence of formaldehyde and tetrahydrofolate analogs under mild conditions, making this a literature-supported protometabolic route to serine rather than an isolated Strecker branch (Anthony, 2011; Morowitz, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Spark-discharge atmospheric synthesis of glycine from simple gases", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_001", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "energetic atmospheric discharge with mineral deposition in surface waters", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing atmosphere; lightning/spark discharge; H2S-rich volcanic variants broaden product set"}, "mechanism": "Energetic atmospheric synthesis delivers glycine and related amino acids into aqueous surface reservoirs.", "reasoning": "Miller-Urey type discharge experiments robustly yield glycine, and reanalysis of sulfur-rich volcanic variants expanded the amino acid inventory relevant to hydroxy amino acid chemistry; this provides an external glycine reservoir feeding serine formation in mild settings (Miller, 1953; Miller, 1957; Parker et al., 2011; Cleaves, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Spark-discharge / volcanic atmospheric synthesis of serine", "inputs": ["mol_002", "mol_003", "mol_001", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "energetic atmospheric processing with deposition into surface pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "lightning/spark discharge; volcanic H2S/CO2 enrichment improves hydroxy amino acid diversity"}, "mechanism": "Radical-driven atmospheric chemistry directly produces a suite of amino acids including serine, later accumulating in cooler aqueous