le hydrolysis occurs in aqueous pools, during geothermal cycling, or at neutral pH interfaces.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.8,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.91,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is the best pathway in the network. Glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN is well established, and thiophosphate-enhanced conversion of glycolonitrile plus HCN to serine nitrile is directly aligned with the cited recent literature. Conversion of serine nitrile to serine is chemically valid. As with P1, the principal weakness is the network's simplified HCN sourcing.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add explicit UV irradiation and thiophosphate provenance details to better reflect Ritson & Sutherland 2023.\",\n        \"Include a defensible formaldehyde source node or reaction rather than leaving it effectively assumed.\",\n        \"Specify mineral/photoredox agents more concretely for the surface chemistry.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.94,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway captures the intended hydrothermal-to-surface integration well. Hydrothermal formate production is plausible and consistent with vent chemistry, and tran